---
import Layout from "../layouts/Layout.astro";

const meta = (await import("../../public/data/meta.json", { assert: { type: "json" } })).default;
const base = import.meta.env.BASE_URL.replace(/\/$/, "");
---

<Layout title="Method — MAPGEN: Cinema's Mirror" station="about">
  <section class="container-kiosk pt-12 pb-32">
    <p class="text-xs uppercase tracking-[0.3em] text-gold-400">Method</p>
    <h1 class="mt-3 font-display text-kiosk-xl text-white max-w-3xl">How this was built.</h1>
    <p class="mt-4 max-w-2xl text-kiosk-md text-white/75 leading-snug">
      For researchers, policy analysts, screenwriters, and anyone who wants to
      know what data informs everything you see in this site — the
      visualizations, the Lens analysis, the Studio diagnostics — before citing
      it or applying it to your work. This page is the boring part, kept honest
      on purpose.
    </p>

    <!-- Plain-language summary for non-technical readers -->
    <div class="mt-10 panel p-6 md:p-8 border-l-2 border-gold-400 bg-gold-400/[0.03]">
      <p class="text-xs uppercase tracking-[0.25em] text-gold-400">In plain language</p>
      <p class="mt-3 text-base text-white/85 leading-relaxed max-w-3xl">
        We collected dialogue lines where a film character feels shame or pride
        — about 12,000 lines, drawn from roughly 5,400 Bollywood and Hollywood
        films. For each line, we recorded who the emotion lands on (a man, a
        woman) and what triggered it (e.g., a character's marital status, a
        son's accomplishment, a public failure). Then we grouped triggers into
        themes and compared the patterns across the two industries. Everything
        on this site is computed from that table.
      </p>
      <p class="mt-3 text-sm text-white/60 leading-relaxed max-w-3xl">
        What we measure is on-screen depictions, not what audiences felt or did.
        The patterns are real; individual readings of any one film or scene
        should be treated as exploratory.
      </p>
    </div>

    <!-- Quick stats -->
    <div class="mt-10 grid gap-3 sm:grid-cols-2 lg:grid-cols-4">
      <div class="panel p-4">
        <p class="font-display text-3xl text-gold-400">{meta.corpus_size.toLocaleString()}</p>
        <p class="text-xs text-white/60 mt-1">labeled dialogues</p>
      </div>
      <div class="panel p-4">
        <p class="font-display text-3xl text-white">{meta.films_matched.toLocaleString()}</p>
        <p class="text-xs text-white/60 mt-1">films in corpus</p>
      </div>
      <div class="panel p-4">
        <p class="font-display text-3xl text-white">{meta.themes.shame + meta.themes.pride}</p>
        <p class="text-xs text-white/60 mt-1">themes ({meta.themes.shame} shame · {meta.themes.pride} pride)</p>
      </div>
      <div class="panel p-4">
        <p class="font-display text-3xl text-white">{meta.gender_coverage_pct}<span class="text-white/30 text-base">%</span></p>
        <p class="text-xs text-white/60 mt-1">of dialogues have a labeled target gender (the person the emotion is directed at)</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- ===== The dataset ===== -->
    <div class="mt-20 grid gap-10 lg:grid-cols-[1fr_280px]">
      <article class="prose-invert max-w-none">
        <h2 class="font-display text-3xl text-white">The dataset</h2>
        <p class="mt-4 text-base text-white/75 leading-relaxed">
          Source: the <em>Cross-Cultural Social Norms Dataset</em>
          (Rai et al., NAACL 2025) — a manually-annotated corpus of dialogue
          excerpts from Bollywood and Hollywood films, each labeled with the
          emotion (shame or pride), the gender of the person experiencing the
          emotion, and the trigger for that emotion.
        </p>
        <p class="mt-4 text-base text-white/75 leading-relaxed">
          We extend the original release with three layers of enrichment, each
          fully reproducible from the scripts in the public repository:
        </p>
        <ol class="mt-4 space-y-3 text-sm text-white/75">
          <li class="flex gap-3">
            <span class="font-display text-gold-400 flex-none">01</span>
            <span><strong class="text-white">TMDB enrichment</strong> — film titles matched to The Movie Database for canonical metadata: year, country, poster, overview. Match rate: 88.9% (97.6% Hollywood, 82.6% Bollywood).</span>
          </li>
          <li class="flex gap-3">
            <span class="font-display text-gold-400 flex-none">02</span>
            <span><strong class="text-white">Theme clustering</strong> — every <code class="text-gold-400/80 text-xs bg-white/5 px-1 rounded">cause</code> string is embedded with OpenAI <code class="text-gold-400/80 text-xs bg-white/5 px-1 rounded">text-embedding-3-small</code>, then Ward-linkage hierarchical clustered into {meta.themes.shame} shame and {meta.themes.pride} pride themes. Cluster labels are LLM-generated and human-verified.</span>
          </li>
          <li class="flex gap-3">
            <span class="font-display text-gold-400 flex-none">03</span>
            <span><strong class="text-white">Gender backfill</strong> — single-shot LLM pass on the 22% of records where the original target_gender field was blank. Cached results go through manual spot-checks; coverage rises to {meta.gender_coverage_pct}% with the back-fill flagged separately in the data.</span>
          </li>
        </ol>
        <p class="mt-4 text-sm text-white/55 italic">
          The pipeline scripts cache every API call, so a full corpus rebuild is
          deterministic and costs ~$2 from cold caches.
        </p>
      </article>

      <!-- Sidebar — links + access -->
      <aside class="lg:sticky lg:top-24 lg:self-start space-y-3">
        <a href={base + "/paper.pdf"} target="_blank" rel="noopener"
           class="panel block p-5 hover:ring-gold-400/40 transition">
          <p class="text-xs uppercase tracking-[0.2em] text-gold-400">Paper</p>
          <p class="mt-2 font-display text-base text-white leading-snug">
            Rai, Sunny et al. (2025). Social Norms in Cinema: A Cross-Cultural Analysis of Shame, Pride and Prejudice. NAACL 2025, pp. 11396–11415.
          </p>
          <p class="mt-3 text-xs text-white/40">Open PDF →</p>
        </a>
        <a href="https://github.com/Khushangz/Cross-Cultural-Social-Norms-Dataset" target="_blank" rel="noopener"
           class="panel block p-5 hover:ring-gold-400/40 transition">
          <p class="text-xs uppercase tracking-[0.2em] text-gold-400">Source dataset</p>
          <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-white/80">CC-BY-SA on GitHub. Raw labels + films list.</p>
          <p class="mt-3 text-xs text-white/40">Khushangz/Cross-Cultural-Social-Norms-Dataset →</p>
        </a>
        <a href="https://github.com/chandrasg/norms-in-cinema-demo" target="_blank" rel="noopener"
           class="panel block p-5 hover:ring-gold-400/40 transition">
          <p class="text-xs uppercase tracking-[0.2em] text-gold-400">This site's source</p>
          <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-white/80">Pipeline + frontend + per-station JSON.</p>
          <p class="mt-3 text-xs text-white/40">chandrasg/norms-in-cinema-demo →</p>
        </a>
      </aside>
    </div>

    <!-- ===== Key formulas ===== -->
    <div class="mt-20">
      <h2 class="font-display text-3xl text-white">Definitions you'll see on the site</h2>

      <div class="mt-6 grid gap-4 md:grid-cols-2">
        <div class="panel p-5 md:p-6">
          <p class="text-xs uppercase tracking-[0.2em] text-gold-400">Δ — cultural delta</p>
          <p class="mt-2 font-display text-base text-white">Used in The Atlas tug-of-war.</p>
          <p class="mt-3 text-sm text-white/65 leading-relaxed">
            For each theme, the share of that emotion in one industry minus the
            share in the other:
          </p>
          <pre class="mt-3 p-3 rounded-md bg-ink-950 text-xs text-white/80 overflow-x-auto"><code>Δ = (n_bolly / N_bolly_emotion) − (n_holly / N_holly_emotion)</code></pre>
          <p class="mt-3 text-xs text-white/45">
            Positive Δ → theme is over-represented in Bollywood relative to its
            share of the emotion overall. Equation 1 in the paper.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="panel p-5 md:p-6">
          <p class="text-xs uppercase tracking-[0.2em] text-gold-400">Convergence score</p>
          <p class="mt-2 font-display text-base text-white">Used in The Studio.</p>
          <p class="mt-3 text-sm text-white/65 leading-relaxed">
            Harmonic mean of a theme's share in each industry — penalizes themes
            that only appear robustly on one side:
          </p>
          <pre class="mt-3 p-3 rounded-md bg-ink-950 text-xs text-white/80 overflow-x-auto"><code>convergence = 2 · share_bolly · share_holly / (share_bolly + share_holly)</code></pre>
          <p class="mt-3 text-xs text-white/45">
            Original to this demo, not in the paper. High convergence = present
            in both industries with similar prominence.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="panel p-5 md:p-6">
          <p class="text-xs uppercase tracking-[0.2em] text-gold-400">Whitespace ratio</p>
          <p class="mt-2 font-display text-base text-white">Used in The Studio.</p>
          <p class="mt-3 text-sm text-white/65 leading-relaxed">
            Ratio of theme shares between the present and absent industries,
            among themes where one side is robust (≥3%) and the other under-tells
            (≤2/5 of that share).
          </p>
          <p class="mt-3 text-xs text-white/45">
            Indicative of cross-cultural storytelling gaps, not a forecasting metric.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="panel p-5 md:p-6">
          <p class="text-xs uppercase tracking-[0.2em] text-gold-400">Era buckets</p>
          <p class="mt-2 font-display text-base text-white">Used in The Mirror &amp; Studio.</p>
          <p class="mt-3 text-sm text-white/65 leading-relaxed">
            Three buckets: <em>pre-2000</em>, <em>2000–2014</em>, <em>2015–present</em>.
            The 2015 cut aligns with the global #MeToo era and major Indian
            legal/social shifts (Nirbhaya aftermath).
          </p>
          <p class="mt-3 text-xs text-white/45">
            Per-era sample sizes vary; the most recent Bollywood pride bucket is
            smallest. Direction is consistent across coverage; exact percentages
            in small buckets warrant caution.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- ===== Limitations ===== -->
    <div class="mt-20">
      <h2 class="font-display text-3xl text-white">What this can &amp; can't be cited for</h2>
      <p class="mt-3 max-w-2xl text-base text-white/70 leading-relaxed">
        We're conservative about the strength of these claims. Use them as
        framing devices and starting points; don't treat them as adjudicated truth.
      </p>

      <div class="mt-8 grid gap-4 md:grid-cols-2">
        <div class="panel p-5 md:p-6 ring-1 ring-emerald-400/20">
          <p class="text-xs uppercase tracking-[0.2em] text-emerald-300">Defensible findings</p>
          <ul class="mt-3 space-y-2 text-sm text-white/75 leading-relaxed">
            <li>• Bollywood uses the explicit vocabulary of shame ~4× more frequently than Hollywood.</li>
            <li>• Female share of <em>shame</em> is roughly stable in both industries (~30%).</li>
            <li>• Female share of <em>pride</em> diverges since 2000 — Hollywood up, Bollywood down.</li>
            <li>• Depictions of shame in Bollywood are often associated with community-policed femininity; Hollywood depictions of shame focus instead on individual failure.</li>
            <li>• Cultural Identity, Patriotism, Family Honor, and Son's Accomplishments are robust Bollywood-only pride themes.</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <div class="panel p-5 md:p-6 ring-1 ring-gold-400/20">
          <p class="text-xs uppercase tracking-[0.2em] text-gold-400">Limitations &amp; cautions</p>
          <ul class="mt-3 space-y-2 text-sm text-white/75 leading-relaxed">
            <li>• Bollywood subtitles are English translations; some cultural register is lost in translation before our pipeline ever runs.</li>
            <li>• The corpus reflects available subtitle availability and is biased toward films with theatrical distribution.</li>
            <li>• Target-gender labels are LLM-assisted on 22% of records.</li>
            <li>• Theme clustering uses Ward linkage; alternative clustering would produce different boundaries and labels.</li>
            <li>• Per-film views (The Lens) have small n; treat as illustrative, not adjudicating.</li>
            <li>• Era buckets are uneven in size; treat percentages in the smallest cells with caution.</li>
            <li>• These findings reflect what films say, not what audiences feel or what societies enact in practice.</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- ===== Citation ===== -->
    <div class="mt-20">
      <h2 class="font-display text-3xl text-white">Citation</h2>
      <p class="mt-3 max-w-2xl text-base text-white/70 leading-relaxed">
        If you reference findings or visualizations from this site, cite the
        underlying paper. If you specifically reference a finding that's
        original to this demo (era trend, convergence score, whitespace map),
        cite the demo URL alongside.
      </p>

      <div class="mt-6 grid gap-4 md:grid-cols-2">
        <div class="panel p-5 md:p-6">
          <p class="text-xs uppercase tracking-[0.2em] text-gold-400">Paper</p>
          <pre class="mt-3 p-4 rounded-md bg-ink-950 text-xs text-white/80 overflow-x-auto leading-relaxed"><code>@inproceedings{`{`}rai2025socialnorms,
  title     = {`{`}Social Norms in Cinema: A Cross-Cultural Analysis of Shame, Pride and Prejudice{`}`},
  author    = {`{`}Rai, Sunny and others{`}`},
  booktitle = {`{`}Proceedings of the 2025 Conference of the Nations of the Americas Chapter of the Association for Computational Linguistics: Human Language Technologies (Volume 1: Long Papers){`}`},
  month     = {`{`}April{`}`},
  year      = {`{`}2025{`}`},
  pages     = {`{`}11396--11415{`}`},
  url       = {`{`}https://aclanthology.org/2025.naacl-long.568{`}`}
{`}`}</code></pre>
        </div>
        <div class="panel p-5 md:p-6">
          <p class="text-xs uppercase tracking-[0.2em] text-gold-400">This demo</p>
          <pre class="mt-3 p-4 rounded-md bg-ink-950 text-xs text-white/80 overflow-x-auto leading-relaxed"><code>@misc{`{`}guntuku2026mapgen,
  title  = {`{`}MAPGEN: Cinema's Mirror — Shame, Pride and Prejudice{`}`},
  author = {`{`}Guntuku, Sharath Chandra and collaborators{`}`},
  year   = {`{`}2026{`}`},
  note   = {`{`}Penn · World Bank · USC Annenberg Norman Lear Center{`}`},
  url    = {`{`}https://chandrasg.github.io/norms-in-cinema-demo{`}`}
{`}`}</code></pre>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- ===== Team & contact ===== -->
    <div class="mt-20">
      <h2 class="font-display text-3xl text-white">Team &amp; contact</h2>
      <div class="mt-6 grid gap-4 md:grid-cols-3">
        <div class="panel p-5">
          <p class="text-xs uppercase tracking-[0.2em] text-gold-400">Project lead</p>
          <p class="mt-2 font-display text-lg text-white">Sharath Chandra Guntuku</p>
          <p class="mt-1 text-sm text-white/60">Computer &amp; Information Science, University of Pennsylvania</p>
          <button type="button"
                  data-mu="c2hhcmF0aGc=" data-md="Y2lzLnVwZW5uLmVkdQ=="
                  class="mt-3 inline-block text-sm text-gold-400 hover:underline">
            Send a message →
          </button>
        </div>
        <div class="panel p-5">
          <p class="text-xs uppercase tracking-[0.2em] text-gold-400">Original paper</p>
          <p class="mt-2 font-display text-lg text-white">Sunny Rai et al.</p>
          <p class="mt-1 text-sm text-white/60">First author, NAACL 2025 paper. Refer to the paper for the original methodology.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="panel p-5">
          <p class="text-xs uppercase tracking-[0.2em] text-gold-400">Partner organizations</p>
          <ul class="mt-2 space-y-1 text-sm text-white/75">
            <li>· University of Pennsylvania</li>
            <li>· World Bank Group</li>
            <li>· USC Annenberg Norman Lear Center</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- ===== V2 / partnerships ===== -->
    <div class="mt-16 panel p-6 md:p-10 border border-gold-400/20 bg-gradient-to-b from-gold-400/[0.04] to-transparent">
      <div class="flex flex-wrap items-baseline gap-2">
        <p class="text-xs uppercase tracking-[0.25em] text-gold-400">V2 partnerships</p>
        <span class="rounded-full bg-emerald-400/10 ring-1 ring-emerald-400/40 text-emerald-300 text-[10px] uppercase tracking-[0.18em] px-2 py-0.5">
          Anchor funder: Gates Foundation
        </span>
      </div>
      <h3 class="mt-2 font-display text-2xl text-white max-w-3xl">
        We're scaling MAPGEN to ~250,000 films across 160 countries.
      </h3>
      <p class="mt-3 max-w-2xl text-sm md:text-base text-white/70 leading-relaxed">
        V2 is supported by the <span class="text-white">Bill &amp; Melinda Gates Foundation</span>
        as the anchor funder. We're building out the corpus, the country
        coverage, and the diagnostic tooling — and we're actively looking for
        co-funders, regional sponsors, festival partners, and pilot
        production slates.
      </p>
      <p class="mt-3 max-w-2xl text-sm md:text-base text-white/70 leading-relaxed">
        If you're a funder, festival, studio, or research institution
        interested in country-level diagnostics, soft-power dashboards, or a
        longitudinal cross-cultural film research program — we'd like to talk.
        Email the project lead or use the form on the home page.
      </p>
      <div class="mt-5 flex flex-wrap gap-3">
        <button type="button"
                data-mu="c2hhcmF0aGc=" data-md="Y2lzLnVwZW5uLmVkdQ=="
                data-ms="MAPGEN V2 partnership"
                class="rounded-full bg-gold-400 text-ink-950 px-5 py-2.5 text-sm font-medium hover:bg-gold-300 transition">
          Email the project lead about V2 →
        </button>
        <a href={base + "/#feedback"}
           class="rounded-full bg-white/5 ring-1 ring-white/10 text-white/80 px-5 py-2.5 text-sm hover:bg-white/10 hover:text-white transition">
          Use the feedback form
        </a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>
</Layout>
